,"assignee":null,"assignees":[],"milestone":null,"comments":8,"created_at":"2021-05-01T15:50:49Z","updated_at":"2021-08-24T12:59:22Z","closed_at":"2021-08-24T12:59:22Z","author_association":"COLLABORATOR","active_lock_reason":null,"body":"This test passes:\r\n\r\n```\r\nfrom <graspologic's tests/test_mase.py module> import make_train_undirected\r\n\r\ndef test_scores_equal():\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    This shows a better way of calculating scores, proving that the list comprehension\r\n    and matrix multiplication method produce the same result.\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    A = np.asarray(make_train_undirected())\r\n    mase = MultipleASE().fit(A)\r\n    Uhat = mase.latent_left_\r\n\r\n    scores = np.asarray([Uhat.T @ graph @ Uhat for graph in list(A)])\r\n    scores_ = Uhat.T @ A @ Uhat\r\n\r\n    assert np.array_equal(scores, scores_)\r\n```\r\n\r\nUhat is a 2D array, A is a 3D array. MASE currently calculates score matrices in a `for` loop, the way that `scores` is calculated -- but numpy lets you do the whole thing in a vectorized way, where `Uhat.T @ A @ Uhat` is equivalent to calling `Uhat.T @ graph @ Uhat` for each graph on the z-axis of `A`, the way that `scores_` is calculated.\r\n\r\nNumpy vectorization usually results in a multiple-orders-of-magnitude speed increase over using for-loops, so it's probably worth changing this (and scouring for other places in the codebase where we use for-loops when we could use numpy vectorization instead)","closed_by":{"login":"loftusa","id":12386450,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjEyMzg2NDUw","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/12386450?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/loftusa","html_url":"https://github.com/loftusa","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/loftusa/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/loftusa/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/loftusa/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/loftusa/starred{/owner}{/repo}","s